[1]
Date: Tue, 24 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: TimeOnLine.com [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1625713_1,00.html>

Call for action to stop spread of 'toxic' MRSA
----------------------------------------------
Urgent action is needed by the Government to combat deadly new
superbugs that [can - Mod.LL] kill healthy young people, a disease
expert gave warning today, 24 May 2005.
Toxin-producing MRSA [methicillin-resistant _Staphylococcus aureus_]
strains similar to the one that killed an 18-year-old Royal Marine
trainee, are already a widespread medical problem in the USA and
account for the majority of _Staphylococcus aureus_ infections in
some areas.
The fit, young recruit developed necrotizing pneumonia and died 2
days after a cut on his leg that he sustained in training became
infected with an MRSA strain that produces the Panton-Valentine
toxin, an inquest heard this week.
Dr Mark Enright, a Bath University expert who is studying the
disease, called on the Government to set up an active monitoring
system, under which all suspicious cases must be referred to the
Health Protection Agency laboratories in Colindale, London. At
present it is left to hospitals to decide whether to submit swabs for
testing. Advice should be issued to all parents warning them to make
sure that they sterilize cuts and grazes on their children's skin and
cover the wound with a plaster, he urged. He criticised the
Government for failing to take a lead on the subject.
"So far the Government is just saying that the infection is really
rare and not to worry. But that is not good enough," Dr Enright told
Times Online.
"The Panton-Valentine Leukocidin (PVL) strains are already becoming a
very serious problem in the US. A doctor working in a Chicago
children's hospital has reported that the majority of the staph
infections treated there are now PVL-producing strains.
Cases have been reported in schools in France, Switzerland and
Australia as well as the USA, where it has affected prisons, health
clubs and the gay community. There are 6000 known cases in the city
of San Francisco. Problems are also now emerging in Asia, where a
hospital recently experienced a large number of cases.
On Fri, 20 May 2005, Dr Marina Morgan, a microbiologist at the Royal
Devon and Exeter Hospital, told an inquest into Mr Campbell-Smith's
death that she had seen 2 cases of the PVL-producing strain of MRSA
in 9 weeks.
But a spokesman for the Health Protection Agency (HPA) today said that PVL
was "extremely rare", adding "It's not something you're routinely going to
get [from] running through brambles." [Brambles are thorny blackberry
vines. - Mod.JW.] The HPA said PVL was produced by fewer than 1.6 percent of
strains of _Staphylococcus aureus_ found in the UK.
The recruit was 4 weeks from the end of his 32-week training course
when he reportedly scratched his legs while running on 31 Oct 2004.
He was admitted to the medical unit, and later taken to the Royal
Devon and Exeter Hospital, where he died on 2 Nov 2004. A post-mortem
examination showed heart and respiratory failure and traces of PVL
production were later found.
[Byline: Jenny Booth]
